A monotone single index model for spatially-referenced
multistate current status data

Snigdha Das1, Minwoo Chae2, Debdeep Pati3, Dipankar Bandyopadhyay4
1Department of Statistics, Texas A&\&&M University
2Department of Industrial and Management Engineering,
Pohang University of Science &\&& Technology
3Department of Statistics, University of Wisconsinâ€“Madison
4Department of Biostatistics, Virginia Commonwealth University
Abstract

Assessment of multistate disease progression is commonplace in biomedical research, such as, in periodontal disease (PD). However, the presence of multistate current status endpoints, where only a single snapshot of each subjectâ€™s progression through disease states is available at a random inspection time after a known starting state, complicates the inferential framework. In addition, these endpoints can be clustered, and spatially associated, where a group of proximally located teeth (within subjects) may experience similar PD status, compared to those distally located. Motivated by a clinical study recording PD progression, we propose a Bayesian semiparametric accelerated failure time model with an inverse-Wishart proposal for accommodating (spatial) random effects, and flexible errors that follow a Dirichlet process mixture of Gaussians. For clinical interpretability, the systematic component of the event times is modeled using a monotone single index model, with the (unknown) link function estimated via a novel integrated basis expansion and basis coefficients endowed with constrained Gaussian process priors. In addition to establishing parameter identifiability, we present scalable computing via a combination of elliptical slice sampling, fast circulant embedding techniques, and smoothing of hard constraints, leading to straightforward estimation of parameters, and state occupation and transition probabilities. Using synthetic data, we study the finite sample properties of our Bayesian estimates, and their performance under model misspecification. We also illustrate our method via application to the real clinical PD dataset.

Keywords: Accelerated failure time model; circulant embedding; clustered data; Dirichlet process; state occupation probability; transition probability.

1 Introduction

Multistate models (Hougaard,, 1999) have gained substantial momentum in biomedical research for event history analysis (Meira-Machado etÂ al.,, 2009), where a subject (or a study unit) can transition reversibly or irreversibly through a succession of intermediate states (reflective of the disease status under consideration) via a longitudinally observed process, before reaching an absorbing state (say, death). Similar to the usual survival data framework, the time-to-events are incomplete (or right-censored), and one observes the transition times and the corresponding states up to a random censoring time for each study unit.

The current literature is inundated with frequentist (Wan,, 2016; Gu,, 2023) and Bayesian (Koslovsky etÂ al.,, 2018) approaches to multistate models for interval-censored data (vanÂ den Hout,, 2016), where subjects are followed longitudinally at multiple time points and the exact transition times are unobserved, but is known to occur within intervals defined by successive observations. However, it is relatively sparse for multistate models under Type-1 interval-censoring, or â€˜current statusâ€™ endpoints (Lan etÂ al.,, 2017; Anyaso-Samuel etÂ al.,, 2023; Anyaso-Samuel and Datta,, 2024), where each subject is observed at a single inspection time after a known starting state, so that the individualâ€™s state is known at two time points: the initial (starting) time and the inspection time, with no further follow-up. Hence, current status data is a special case of interval-censored data, and arises naturally in clinical trials, epidemiological studies, and surveys. Unlike longitudinal data, which provides detailed individual-level information on transitions between states over time, current status data offers limited insight on transitions due to its cross-sectional nature. This limitation necessitates specialized modeling approaches, as discussed in Chapter 8.2 of vanÂ den Hout, (2016).

The motivation for this work comes from a cross-sectional study assessing periodontal disease (PD) status and progression among Gullah-speaking African-American Type-2 Diabetics (henceforth, GAAD; Fernandes etÂ al.,, 2009). Here, the PD progression can be characterized as a multistate model, where the PD status pertaining to each tooth of a patient is classified into multiple states, according to PD severity, and are current status in nature. The modeling framework is further exacerbated by the presence of event times that are (a) correlated (current status tooth event times are clustered within subjects), and (b) with possible spatial association, since PD status of proximally-located teeth are hypothesized to be similar, and varying with regards to distally-located teeth (Reich and Bandyopadhyay,, 2010). Furthermore, (c) existing literature on multistate regression lacks the development of an interpretable index summarizing the overall risk status of a subject. Specifically, Lan etÂ al., (2017) and Anyaso-Samuel etÂ al., (2023) developed univariate and multivariate regression approaches, respectively, accounting for informative cluster sizes and present risk estimates separately for each covariate, while Anyaso-Samuel and Datta, (2024) focus on the conditional estimation of future state occupation probabilities given prior occupation of specific states. The objective of this paper is to develop a clinically interpretable index within a multistate framework using a novel Bayesian nonparametric model with spatial random effects that account for the intraoral structure of teeth. The index combines the effect of all the risk factors into a single-number summary that informs and predicts the probabilities of occupying and transitioning through the PD states over time. However, note that the generic scientific question addressed in this work extends beyond one specific disease area (PD). Similar data structure and associated challenges, such as multistate models with current status endpoints, correlated pattern, and spatial association, can be observed in other biomedical domains, such as in cancer screening (breast/colorectal), infectious disease progression (COVID-19, tuberculosis), and organ transplantation (kidney graft survival).

In the absence of a unified framework addressing challenges (aâ€“c) for developing an interpretable index, we adopt a semiparametric accelerated failure time (AFT) regression approach (Henderson etÂ al.,, 2020) for the time to the absorbing disease state, motivated by our naive preliminary analysis (presented in Section A of the Supplement). The latent survival times are linked to the observed state occupations by relative increments of time to each state that are Dirichlet distributed. Our hierarchical Bayes framework is the first of its kind, offering several innovations. First, we move away from the traditional Cox proportional hazards regression framework, where violations of the proportional hazards assumption may lead to imprecise inference, and further relax the (restrictive) parametric assumptions of the AFT errors by assigning a Dirichlet process mixture prior (Sethuraman,, 1994) of Gaussians. Second, the systematic component of the survival time is modeled through a flexible and clinically interpretable monotone single index model (SIM, Balabdaoui etÂ al.,, 2019), with the unknown link function estimated via a novel integrated basis expansion (Maatouk and Bay,, 2017) and constrained Gaussian process priors on the basis coefficients. Posterior sampling is performed using the algorithm of Ray etÂ al., (2020), which uses a combination of the efficient elliptical slice sampling (Murray etÂ al.,, 2010), fast circulant embedding techniques (Wood and Chan,, 1994) and smooth relaxation of hard constraints. Third, the intraoral spatial association among teeth for each subject is accounted for via multivariate Gaussian random effects, with an inverse-Wishart prior on its covariance matrix that is centered around a conditionally autoregressive model encouraging association between neighboring teeth. Finally, our model allows for uncertainty quantification of disease state occupation probabilities (SOPs) and transition probabilities (TPs) over time, with individual trajectories described by the single index and thus interpretable in terms of the risk factors for PD.

The rest of the paper proceeds as follows. Section 2 presents the statistical model, and develops the Bayesian inferential framework. While Section 3 illustrates the model via application to the motivating GAAD data, Section 4 conducts simulation studies to assess finite sample properties of our model estimates, and the robustness of our proposed model under misspecification. Finally, Section 5 concludes, alluding to some future work.

2.2 Identifiability of parameters

In the following, we establish the identifiability of the fixed effects parameters in our model, in the presence of (spatial) random-effects. Previous research, often restricted to the iid setup, proved parameter identifiability (Lin and Kulasekera,, 2007) in a SIM for non-constant and continuous functions gğ‘”gitalic_g, under the assumptions that â€–ğœ·â€–=1normğœ·1\|\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}\|=1âˆ¥ bold_italic_Î² âˆ¥ = 1, and the first non-zero element of ğœ·ğœ·\betabold_italic_Î² being positive. For our monotone gğ‘”gitalic_g, a relaxed assumption of only â€–ğœ·â€–=1normğœ·1\|\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}\|=1âˆ¥ bold_italic_Î² âˆ¥ = 1 suffices. To that end, identifiability of the variance components of our model is first established in Proposition 2.1, followed by the proof of identifiability for the fixed effects in Proposition 2.2. The proofs can be found in Section B of the Supplement.

2.3 Bayesian inference

In this section, we develop the Bayesian inferential framework for our proposed model by defining suitable priors for the model parameters. Posterior samples are simulated through the implementation of Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods. We elaborate on the choice of priors in the following, while deferring detailed derivations of full conditionals and posterior sampling strategies to Section C of the Supplement.

2.3.1 Prior for the regression parameters

Since ğœ·ğœ·\betabold_italic_Î² is constrained to have unit norm, we put a normalized Gaussian prior on ğœ·ğœ·\betabold_italic_Î² i.e.let ~â¢ğœ·âˆ¼ğ’©â¢(0,ÏƒÎ²2â¢ğ•€p)similar-to~absentğœ·ğ’©0superscriptsubscriptğœğ›½2subscriptğ•€ğ‘\widetilde{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma_{\beta}^{2}\mathbb% {I}_{p})over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² âˆ¼ caligraphic_N ( 0 , italic_Ïƒ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î² end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT blackboard_I start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) and set ğœ·=~â¢ğœ·/â€–~â¢ğœ·â€–ğœ·~absentğœ·norm~absentğœ·\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}=\widetilde{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}/\|\widetilde{}% \mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}\|bold_italic_Î² = over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² / âˆ¥ over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² âˆ¥. Posterior sampling is done using an efficient elliptical slice sampler (Murray etÂ al.,, 2010), particularly suited for performing inference in models with multivariate Gaussian priors.

2.3.2 Model and prior for the monotone link function

A general approach to Bayesian monotone function estimation is to expand the unknown function in a basis and translate the functional constraints to linear constraints in the coefficient space. Most widely used examples include Bernstein polynomials (BP; Wang and Ghosh,, 2012) and monotone splines (Meyer etÂ al.,, 2011) as the basis choices. Monotonicity of a function is enforced in a BP basis expansion by ordering the coefficients, but this condition is only sufficient and not necessary. There may exist monotone functions for which the BP basis expansion results in unordered coefficients, and can lead to poor approximation (see Figures 4.1, and 4.2). Alternatively, higher order monotone splines are used for capturing the underlying smoothness of a function (Wang and Li,, 2008).

In this article, we consider first order monotone splines to expand the function gğ‘”gitalic_g in a basis and enforce smoothness through an equivalently constrained Gaussian process (GP) on the basis coefficients, as in Maatouk and Bay, (2017). Adapting the notation of Maatouk and Bay, (2017), we begin with defining a regular grid of L+1ğ¿1L+1italic_L + 1 equi-spaced knot points, ul=Î´Lâ¢(lâˆ’L/2)subscriptğ‘¢ğ‘™subscriptğ›¿ğ¿ğ‘™ğ¿2u_{l}=\delta_{L}(l-L/2)italic_u start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_l end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_Î´ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_l - italic_L / 2 ), with Î´L=2/Lsubscriptğ›¿ğ¿2ğ¿\delta_{L}=2/Litalic_Î´ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_L end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 2 / italic_L, l=0,1,â€¦,Lğ‘™01â€¦ğ¿l=0,1,\ldots,Litalic_l = 0 , 1 , â€¦ , italic_L, in the closed interval [âˆ’1,1]11[-1,1][ - 1 , 1 ]. 2.3.3 Prior for the covariance matrix of the spatial random effects

The undirected graph GğºGitalic_G in Figure 2.1 connects neighboring teeth in the upper jaw. 3 Application: GAAD data

In this section, we illustrate our methodology via application to the GAAD dataset. Progression of PD is usually assessed via clinical attachment level (CAL; Bandyopadhyay and Canale,, 2016), defined as the distance (in mm whole numbers) down a toothâ€™s root that is no longer attached to the surrounding bone by the periodontal ligament, and recorded at six pre-specified tooth sites for each of the 28282828 teeth, excluding the four third molars. Following the definition (Wiebe and Putnins,, 2000) of chronic periodontitis severity, our tooth-level PD status comprises average CAL (avCAL) at the corresponding tooth-sites, and categorized into 4444 states: 00 denotes slight PD (avCAL âˆˆ[0,2)absent02\in[0,2)âˆˆ [ 0 , 2 ) mm), 1111 denotes moderate PD (avCAL âˆˆ[2,5)absent25\in[2,5)âˆˆ [ 2 , 5 ) mm), 2222 denotes severe PD (avCAL â‰¥5absent5\geq 5â‰¥ 5 mm) and 3333 denotes missing tooth (avCAL is unavailable, due to past PD). The natural history of chronic PD can be viewed as a staged progressive disease process, from gingivitis to periodontitis characterized by irreversible pathological changes (Mdala etÂ al.,, 2014), as shown in Figure 2.1. In cross-sectional studies like GAAD, the true inspection time for each tooth should be calculated from the adult tooth emergence time, which is typically unavailable. In lieu of this, we approximate the tooth inspection time for all subjects by taking the difference between the subjectâ€™s age (recorded at clinic visit) and the permanent dentition times of US adults published by the American Dental Association, (2022). The data includes n=288ğ‘›288n=288italic_n = 288 subjects with m=28ğ‘š28m=28italic_m = 28 teeth for each subject, 46%percent4646\%46 % of which are in state 00, 19%percent1919\%19 % in state 1111, 2%percent22\%2 % in state 2 and the remaining 32%percent3232\%32 % in state 3333. The subjects have a mean age of 55555555 years, ranging from 26 to 87 years. Around 76%percent7676\%76 % of the subjects are female, 68%percent6868\%68 % are categorized as obese (with a BMI â‰¥\geqâ‰¥ 30), 31%percent3131\%31 % are smokers, and 59%percent5959\%59 % have uncontrolled HbA1c levels. BMI, being a continuous covariate is standardized to have mean 00 and variance 1111.

We considered six competing models during data fitting, which differ in terms of their specifications for the monotone link basis, random effects, and distribution of random errors:

  1. 1.

    S-GP-DP: Spatial random effects with constrained GP basis for the link function, and DP mixture prior on the error density â€“ our proposed model.

  2. 2.

    S-BP-DP: Spatial random effects with Bernstein polynomial (BP) basis for the link function and DP mixture prior on the error density.

  3. 3.

    S-GP-N: Spatial random effects with constrained GP basis for the link function, and normal density for errors.

  4. 4.

    S-BP-N: Spatial random effects with BP basis for the link function, and normal density for errors.

  5. 5.

    S-lin-DP: Linear model (identity link) with spatial random effects, and DP mixture prior on the error density.

  6. 6.

    NS-GP-DP: Non-spatial random effects at the subject-level (biâ¢1=â€¦=biâ¢m=bisubscriptğ‘ğ‘–1â€¦subscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘šsubscriptğ‘ğ‘–b_{i1}=\ldots=b_{im}=b_{i}italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = â€¦ = italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT) with constrained GP basis for the link function, and DP mixture prior on the error density.

For our analysis, we set ÏƒÎ²2=100superscriptsubscriptğœğ›½2100\sigma_{\beta}^{2}=100italic_Ïƒ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î² end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = 100, though any arbitrary positive value can be used since Î²~~ğ›½\tilde{\beta}over~ start_ARG italic_Î² end_ARG is scaled by its norm. For the link function, we use default choices of Î½=0.75ğœˆ0.75\nu=0.75italic_Î½ = 0.75, with â„“â„“\ellroman_â„“ chosen such that the correlation at a maximum covariate separation is 0.050.050.050.05 (Ray etÂ al.,, 2020), and set Î·=100,aÎ¾=0.01formulae-sequenceğœ‚100subscriptğ‘ğœ‰0.01\eta=100,a_{\xi}=0.01italic_Î· = 100 , italic_a start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î¾ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0.01 and bÎ¾=0.01subscriptğ‘ğœ‰0.01b_{\xi}=0.01italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î¾ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0.01. The degree of spatial dependence is set to Ï=0.9ğœŒ0.9\rho=0.9italic_Ï = 0.9 in the prior on Î£bsubscriptÎ£ğ‘\Sigma_{b}roman_Î£ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. For the DP mixture, we set H=10ğ»10H=10italic_H = 10, Î¼Ïµ=0subscriptğœ‡italic-Ïµ0\mu_{\epsilon}=0italic_Î¼ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Ïµ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, Î½Ïµ=1subscriptğœˆitalic-Ïµ1\nu_{\epsilon}=1italic_Î½ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Ïµ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 1, and choose aÏµsubscriptğ‘italic-Ïµa_{\epsilon}italic_a start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Ïµ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, bÏµsubscriptğ‘italic-Ïµb_{\epsilon}italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Ïµ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT to yield a prior mean and variance of sh2superscriptsubscriptğ‘ â„2s_{h}^{2}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_h end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT as 0.10.10.10.1 and 10101010, respectively. The parameters in the gamma prior on Î³ğ›¾\gammaitalic_Î³ is chosen to have mean 1111 and variance 10101010. Since information on the state transition times from the observed data is weak, we use a weakly informative gamma prior on ğœ¶ğœ¶\alphabold_italic_Î± with mean 1111 and variance 100100100100. More details on the choice hyperparameters for each prior are provided in Section E.1 of the Supplement.

We generated posterior MCMC samples of size 70,000 iterations with a burn-in of 20,000 and collected every 50th sample to thin the chain. Posterior convergence was assessed using trace plots and the Gelman-Rubin statistic R^^ğ‘…\hat{R}over^ start_ARG italic_R end_ARG. For model selection tools, we considered the Watanabe-Akaike information criterion (WAIC), and the leave-one-out cross-validation (LOO-IC) using Pareto-smoothed importance sampling available in R package loo, and enlist them in Table 3.1. Models with smaller WAIC and LOO-IC values suggest a better fit to the observed data. For all models except (5), the optimal number of basis functions Lğ¿Litalic_L was set to 30303030, chosen by minimizing WAIC as Lğ¿Litalic_L varied from 10 to 45 in increments of 5; details are provided in Section E.2 of the Supplement.

The non-spatial model having the highest value of both WAIC and LOO-IC validates the necessity of incorporating the intraoral spatial dependencies between the teeth. Among the spatial models, the 3 models having a DP mixture prior on the error density have lower WAIC and LOO-IC, warranting the improved flexibility of DP over normal errors. This is further supported by the larger variability observed in the boxplots of model-based residuals for the models with a normal errors, compared to the DP errors; see Section E.3 of the Supplement. The models with constrained GP basis for the monotone link show better predictive performance compared to the corresponding ones with BP basis. Clearly, our proposed S-GP-DP model outperforms all its competitors.

3.1 Estimation of fixed effects and spatial dependence

Posterior estimates and 95%percent9595\%95 % credible intervals (CIs) of the regression parameters obtained from fitting the six competing models are presented in Figure 1(a). The CI for upper jaw (maxilla) excluded 00, and the posterior estimates were negative with highest magnitude for all six models, indicating that this covariate has the strongest influence on the index. Consequently, the index and hence the survival time, for a maxillary tooth is lower than that for a mandibular tooth. This is in tune with findings revealing higher loss and extraction of maxillary tooth, than mandibular, due to PD (Chraibi etÂ al.,, 2023). Strong evidence of a higher index is observed in females compared to males from the S-GP-DP, S-BP-N and NS-GP-DP models, resonating with higher prevalence of chronic PD in males (Ioannidou,, 2017). This association, however, lacks significance (though positive) in the other models. Smoking is revealed to negatively impact the index in all models, leading to reduced survival, thereby corroborating with published literature (Zee,, 2009), with significant impact in the S-GP-DP and NS-GP-DP models. BMI and glycemic levels do not seem to significantly affect the index, with the exception of a strong negative impact of HbA1c in the NS-GP-DP model.

Figure 1(b) plots the link functions estimated from the models, along with their 95%percent9595\%95 % CIs. The range of the link functions estimated by the three models having constrained GP basis are similar. The spatial models with BP basis and normal errors have a higher range, while that with DP mixture errors has a very low range. This is in alignment with the performance of these models in our simulation studies (see Section 4 for details). The estimates expâ¡(g^â¢(Î²l^)âˆ’g^â¢(0))^ğ‘”^subscriptğ›½ğ‘™^ğ‘”0\exp(\hat{g}(\hat{\beta_{l}})-\hat{g}(0))roman_exp ( over^ start_ARG italic_g end_ARG ( over^ start_ARG italic_Î² start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_l end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_ARG ) - over^ start_ARG italic_g end_ARG ( 0 ) ) for the significant predictors i.e.gender, smoking and maxilla from our S-GP-DP model indicate females have approximately 2.22.22.22.2 times the survival time of males, smokers have about 0.650.650.650.65 times that of non-smokers, and maxillary teeth exhibit a survival time of 0.30.30.30.3 times that of mandibular teeth. The S-GP-N and S-BP-N models show similar estimates. These estimates from the S-BP-DP model are close to 1111 for all predictors, as evident from the low range of its estimated link function. The NS-GP-DP model additionally identifies glycemic level as a significant predictor, showing that a high glycemic level reduces survival time to 0.56 times that of a low level.

Heatmaps of the posterior estimate of the precision matrix Î©bsubscriptÎ©ğ‘\Omega_{b}roman_Î© start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT of the random effects in the five spatial models are illustrated in Figure 1(c). Strong correlations are seen between first molars (teeth 2 and 13), which are mirror images in opposite maxillary quadrants, consistent with clinical findings which highlight that molars and premolars generally exhibit higher levels of PD (Kindler etÂ al.,, 2018). The matrices are mostly concentrated along their tridiagonal, confirming the neighborhood association depicted in Figure 2.1 and suggests that spatial dependence weakens considerably beyond the immediate neighboring tooth.

3.2 Estimation of state occupation and transition probabilities

To illustrate the use of our model to probe the association between a covariate and the state occupation and transition probabilities of teeth, we arbitrarily consider a female smoker aged 56 years (median), with a BMI of 35.33 (mean) and uncontrolled HbA1c. Figure 3.2 plots the posterior mean and 95%percent9595\%95 % CI of the SOPs over the years 10â€“80, and TPs for the next 10 years (with the baseline age set to the median of 56 years), for the maxillary (upper jaw) and mandibular (lower jaw) second molar (teeth numbers 1 and 28, respectively) of this subject, based on 10,000 Monte Carlo samples. On the overall, our model indicates that maxillary location negatively affects tooth survival. The SOPs for state 00 decreases while that for state 3333 increase over time, with the mandibular molar having higher (lower) SOP for state 0 (3), than that of the maxillary counterpart, as one would naturally expect. Consequently, intersecting trajectories for the SOPs of states 1111 and 2222 was observed, initially showing an increasing trend for both jaws before decreasing, with the change-point occurring at a higher age for mandible than that for maxilla.

To collectively summarize the combined effect of all the covariates on these probabilities, Figure 3.2 plots the posterior mean and 95%percent9595\%95 % CIs of the SOPs over the years 10â€“80, and TPs for the next 10 years, corresponding to the minimum, median and maximum value of the estimated index u^iâ¢j=ğ’™iâ¢jâŠ¤â¢^â¢ğœ·subscript^ğ‘¢ğ‘–ğ‘—superscriptsubscriptğ’™ğ‘–ğ‘—top^absentğœ·\hat{u}_{ij}=\bm{x}_{ij}^{\top}\hat{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}over^ start_ARG italic_u end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT âŠ¤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT over^ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î², where ğœ·^^ğœ·\hat{\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}}over^ start_ARG bold_italic_Î² end_ARG denotes the posterior mean of ğœ·ğœ·\betabold_italic_Î². The baseline age for the TPs is again set to 56 years (median). Quite intuitively, patterns similar to Figure 3.2 are observed. Decreasing (increasing) trend in the SOP of states 0 (state 3) is observed, with a higher probability at any given time for a higher index, with intersecting trajectories for states 1 and 2. A lower index corresponds to an elevated chance of transitioning to a higher state of the disease at any given time. We further note that the estimated probability of occupying state 2222 and that of transitioning from state 1111 to state 2222 is quite low compared to the other SOPs and TPs respectively. This can be partially attributed to the fact that only 2%percent22\%2 % of the observations in our data occupied state 2222.

4 Simulation studies

In this section, we conduct simulations using synthetic data to (a) investigate the frequentist finite sample properties, and (b) the effect of model misspecification in recovering the regression parameters ğœ·ğœ·\betabold_italic_Î², and the link function gğ‘”gitalic_g, while using our proposed model. Henceforth, we refer to them as Simulations 1 and 2, respectively, and compare the performances of models (1)â€“(4) outlined in Section 3.

At the onset, we outline the data generating process followed in the two simulation settings. Our data generation mimics a practical setting as observed in the GAAD study. We consider p=3ğ‘3p=3italic_p = 3 covariates, the highest disease state K=3ğ¾3K=3italic_K = 3, m=10ğ‘š10m=10italic_m = 10 teeth for every subject, and vary the sample size as n=50,100,300ğ‘›50100300n=50,100,300italic_n = 50 , 100 , 300 and 500500500500. The data generation steps are as follows:

For all competing models, we conduct MCMC sampling for 7,000 iterations and discard the first 5,000 as burn-in. Posterior estimates are summarized over 100100100100 simulation replicates. Results considering the true link function as g10subscriptsuperscriptğ‘”01g^{0}_{1}italic_g start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT are presented here, while those from g20subscriptsuperscriptğ‘”02g^{0}_{2}italic_g start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT are deferred to Section F of the Supplement. We provide boxplots of the MSE, RB and MISE and barplots of the CP across the 100 replicates over increasing nğ‘›nitalic_n under Simulations 1 and 2 in Figures 4.1 and 4.2 respectively.

Simulation 1: When the model is correctly specified, the S-GP-DP and S-GP-N models yield an overall superior estimation performance than the models with BP basis. Decreasing trends in the boxplots of MSE, RB and MISE with increasing sample sizes imply posterior estimates from the models with constrained GP basis are consistent. The desired 95%percent9595\%95 % coverage is attained by each Î²^jsubscript^ğ›½ğ‘—\hat{\beta}_{j}over^ start_ARG italic_Î² end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT for both small and large sample sizes. While S-BP-N shows a poor performance in terms of all aforementioned metrics, the S-BP-DP model shows an overall worse performance.

Simulation 2: When the model is misspecified, the S-GP-DP and S-GP-N models are again seen to yield an overall superior estimation performance, compared to the S-BP-DP and S-BP-N. The GP models deliver satisfactory estimation performances in terms of MSE, RB and MISE. The GP models attain the desired 95%percent9595\%95 % coverage across all sample sizes. Though S-BP-N attains the nominal CP, the coverage of S-BP-DP falls sharply with increasing sample size (1%percent11\%1 % for n=500ğ‘›500n=500italic_n = 500). The regression parameter estimates from the S-BP-N appear to be robust for all sample sizes, however, the estimation of the link function worsens acutely with increase in the sample size. Estimation of the link function and the regression parameters are observed to be poor under the S-BP-DP model. To summarize, estimates from the GP models are found to be robust under model misspecification. While the estimation of the link function under the S-BP-N model suffers for large sample sizes, the S-BP-DP model delivers poor performances across all sample sizes.

The poor performance of the BP-DP model can be attributed to the global nature of the BP basis, where the identifiability constraint (gâ¢(âˆ’1)=0ğ‘”10g(-1)=0italic_g ( - 1 ) = 0) impacts the overall flexibility of the link function estimation, unlike the local basis used in the GP method. Additionally, the BP-DP model faces the challenge of simultaneously estimating both the link function and the error density, whereas the BP-N model benefits from a fixed Gaussian assumption for the error distribution, enabling better recovery of the link function.

5 Conclusions

Motivated by a cross-sectional PD study, we introduce a novel framework for estimating a clinically interpretable tooth-level disease risk index within a multistate model, accounting for spatially-referenced current status data. Our approach leverages advanced posterior sampling techniques, such as elliptical slice sampling and circulant embedding, to address computational challenges. Applied to the GAAD data, our model confirms higher PD risk among males and smokers (Genco and Borgnakke,, 2013), but, consistent with our preliminary results, does not reveal a significant association between HbA1c levels and PD progression.

We estimate transition probabilities under the assumption that future transitions depend only on the current state. While incorporating sojourn times (i.e.the duration a tooth remains in a particular state before transitioning) could be considered, this is challenging under the current status framework. Our model adopts a forward tracking structure, reflecting the progressive nature of PD (Coventry etÂ al.,, 2000), but could be extended to allow reversible transitions, as relevant in other diseases. We also assume independent censoring; relaxing this to allow for informative inspection times, (e.g., via copula models (Zhao etÂ al.,, 2015)), is complex and presents a separate scope of future study. Recent advances in single index models using neural networks (Bietti etÂ al.,, 2022) do not enforce monotonicity of the link function, which is key for clinical interpretability. Integrating machine learning tools to estimate monotone SIMs is a promising future direction. Moreover, while advanced areal spatial models, such as the Directed Acyclic Graph Auto-Regressive model (Datta etÂ al.,, 2019) exist, we opt for a simpler inverse-Wishart approach to avoid complicating our existing framework on monotone link function and error density estimation. This aims to mitigate potential mixing issues that may arise from introducing additional complexities to the model.

Finally, our analysis of the GAAD dataset reveals its limitations, including only four subject-level covariates and a relatively small sample size, in light of recently available databases of larger dimensions. Extending our approach to larger cross-sectional studies like NHANES (CDC,, 1996) will require significant computational enhancements, but the availability of abundant covariates in such databases could facilitate techniques such as variable selection within the single index framework to construct an interpretable index.

Supplementary Materials

This supplement contains a preliminary analysis of the GAAD data, proof of results on model identifiability, blocked full conditional posterior distribution of parameters, details on estimation of state occupation and transition probabilities, additional details on the GAAD data analysis, and additional simulation results. Code for implementing our model is available at the GitHub repository, das-snigdha/BayesSPMSM.

Appendix A GAAD data: some specifics and preliminary analysis

For an initial preliminary analysis, we converted the multistate responses of the GAAD data (see Section 3 of the main document for details) into interval-censored, corresponding to tooth occupying state 3333, i.e.Â tooth loss.

Figure A.1 presents the nonparametric Turnbull estimates (Turnbull,, 1976) of tooth-level survival curves, grouped by smoking status and HbA1c, revealing worse survival for smokers, but overlapping curves for the HbA1c levels. Furthermore, a fitted accelerated failure time (AFT) model (with Weibull errors) incorporating squared BMI and interactions between smoking, gender and HbA1c along with the main covariates, reveals smoking, jaw indicator and smokingÃ—\timesÃ—gender interaction to be strongly significant predictors. Additionally, squared BMI and smokingÃ—\timesÃ—HbA1c interaction were marginally significant. This provides an indication for the presence of non-linearity in covariates. The absence of a clear unified strategy that accommodates non-linearity and interactions to yield a concise and interpretable single-number summary motivates us to develop a holistic AFT regression approach, incorporating monotone single index model within a progressive multistate modeling framework that facilitates efficient risk quantification on the entire tooth decay process via automatic consideration of non-linear main effects and higher order interactions through a scalar single index.

Appendix B Identifiability of parameters

In the following, we provide the proofs of Propositions 2.1 and 2.2, which establishes the identifiability of the variance components and fixed effects parameters of our proposed model.

Appendix C Posterior Computation

This section enlists detailed derivations of the blocked full conditional distributions of the parameters and the latent variables of our model, along with their posterior sampling schemes. Recall from Section 2.3.4 of the main document that a Dirichlet process (DP) mixture prior of Gaussians on the baseline density fğ‘“fitalic_f of the errors posits that

Appendix E Additional details on the GAAD data analysis

E.1 Choice of hyperparameters

In this section, we elaborate on the choice of hyperparameters which characterize the prior distributions on our model parameters, used in the GAAD data analysis.

Regression parameters: We use a zero-mean Gaussian prior on ~â¢ğœ·~absentğœ·\widetilde{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² and set its prior variance ÏƒÎ²2=100superscriptsubscriptğœğ›½2100\sigma_{\beta}^{2}=100italic_Ïƒ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î² end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = 100. However, any arbitrary choice for ÏƒÎ²2superscriptsubscriptğœğ›½2\sigma_{\beta}^{2}italic_Ïƒ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î² end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT would suffice, as long as it is positive. Since ~â¢ğœ·~absentğœ·\widetilde{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² is scaled by its norm, the variance of the induced prior on Î²ğ›½\betaitalic_Î² remains unaffected by the specific choice of ÏƒÎ²2superscriptsubscriptğœğ›½2\sigma_{\beta}^{2}italic_Ïƒ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î² end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. Additionally, one can specify a non-zero mean Î¼ğœ‡\muitalic_Î¼ for ~â¢ğœ·~absentğœ·\widetilde{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² to reflect prior knowledge about certain covariates. To accommodate this, we need to apply a simple modification to the elliptical slice sampling algorithm for posterior sampling of ~â¢ğœ·~absentğœ·\widetilde{}\mbox{\boldmath$\beta$}over~ start_ARG end_ARG bold_italic_Î² to adjust for its non-zero mean. Details on implementing this adjustment can be found in Section 3.3 of Murray etÂ al., (2010).

Monotone link function: The length-scale parameter â„“â„“\ellroman_â„“ of the MatÃ©rn covariance kernel (discussed in Section C.2) controls the rate of decay of the covariance with the inter-location distances, and is usually chosen to ensure very small correlation between two distant points in the covariate space. The parameter Î½ğœˆ\nuitalic_Î½ controls the smoothness of the monotone function gğ‘”gitalic_g. We know that the reproducing kernel Hilbert space of a Gaussian process equipped with MatÃ©rn covariance kernel with smoothness parameter Î½ğœˆ\nuitalic_Î½ consists of functions belonging to the HÃ¶lder class of smoothness Î½+0.5ğœˆ0.5\nu+0.5italic_Î½ + 0.5. Following Ray etÂ al., (2020), we use default choices of Î½=0.75ğœˆ0.75\nu=0.75italic_Î½ = 0.75, with â„“â„“\ellroman_â„“ chosen such that the correlation at a maximum possible separation between the covariates equals 0.050.050.050.05. When using a smooth relaxation of the indicator function in the constrained prior of the basis coefficients in equation (2.9) of the main document, we set Î·=100ğœ‚100\eta=100italic_Î· = 100. To have a non-informative inverse-gamma â„â¢ğ’¢â¢(aÎ¾,bÎ¾)â„ğ’¢subscriptğ‘ğœ‰subscriptğ‘ğœ‰\mathcal{IG}(a_{\xi},b_{\xi})caligraphic_I caligraphic_G ( italic_a start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î¾ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Î¾ end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) prior on Ï„2superscriptğœ2\tau^{2}italic_Ï„ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, both the parameters are set to 0.010.010.010.01.

E.2 Selection of knots in the basis expansion of the monotone link function

We vary the number of knot points Lâˆˆ{10,15,20,â€¦,45}ğ¿101520â€¦45L\in\{10,15,20,\ldots,45\}italic_L âˆˆ { 10 , 15 , 20 , â€¦ , 45 } in the basis expansion of the monotone link function, given in equation (2.7) of the main document. By fitting the four competing spatial models to the GAAD data (see Section 3 of the main document for details), we calculate the corresponding values of Watanabe-Akaike information criterion (WAIC) for each knot point. In Figure E.1, the plotted WAIC values against the number of knots reveal a clear pattern: the S-GP-DP model consistently exhibits the lowest WAIC across all knot points, followed by the S-BP-DP model. Models employing DP errors consistently outperform those with normal errors in terms of WAIC. For the S-GP-DP model, the lowest WAIC occurs at L=35ğ¿35L=35italic_L = 35, followed by L=30ğ¿30L=30italic_L = 30 with a difference of less than 10101010. Consequently, we select L=30ğ¿30L=30italic_L = 30 for our analysis of the GAAD data.

E.3 Plot of model based residuals

We define the model based residuals as eiâ¢j=logÂ â¢Tiâ¢jâˆ’biâ¢jâˆ’gâ¢(ğ’™iâ¢jâŠ¤â¢Î²)âˆ’Ï•ziâ¢jsubscriptğ‘’ğ‘–ğ‘—logÂ subscriptğ‘‡ğ‘–ğ‘—subscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘—ğ‘”superscriptsubscriptğ’™ğ‘–ğ‘—topğ›½subscriptitalic-Ï•subscriptğ‘§ğ‘–ğ‘—e_{ij}=\text{log }T_{ij}-b_{ij}-g(\bm{x}_{ij}^{\top}\beta)-\phi_{z_{ij}}italic_e start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = log italic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT - italic_b start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT - italic_g ( bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT âŠ¤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_Î² ) - italic_Ï• start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_z start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT for each iğ‘–iitalic_i, jğ‘—jitalic_j. Figure E.2 shows boxplots of these residuals for the S-GP-DP and S-GP-N models. It is evident that the model with a normal prior for the error density exhibits greater variability in residuals around zero in comparison to the model employing a DP mixture prior.

Appendix F Additional simulation results

In this section, we present the results of Simulations 1 and 2 when the underlying true link function is g20superscriptsubscriptğ‘”20g_{2}^{0}italic_g start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 0 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. Boxplots of the mean squared error (MSE), relative bias (RB) and mean integrated squared error (MISE) and barplots of the coverage probability (CP) across the 100 replicates over increasing nğ‘›nitalic_n under Simulations 1 and 2 are shown in Figures F.1 and F.2, respectively.

Under Simulation 1, where the model is correctly specified, both the S-GP-DP and S-GP-N models demonstrate superior estimation performance compared to models employing the BP basis. The boxplots of MSE, RB, and MISE exhibit a decreasing trend as sample sizes increases, indicating that posterior estimates from models with constrained GP basis are consistent. The desired 95%percent9595\%95 % coverage is attained by each Î²^jsubscript^ğ›½ğ‘—\hat{\beta}_{j}over^ start_ARG italic_Î² end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT for both small and large sample sizes. The S-BP-N model shows comparable performance for sample sizes (50, 100, 300) but the performance deteriorates for sample size 500. The S-BP-DP model demonstrates uniformly poor performance for all sample sizes.

Under Simulation 2, where the model is misspecified, the S-GP-DP and S-GP-N models consistently outperform the S-BP-DP and S-BP-N models. The GP models deliver satisfactory estimation performances in terms of MSE, RB and MISE. The GP models attain the desired 95%percent9595\%95 % coverage across all sample sizes. While S-BP-N maintains the nominal coverage rate, the coverage of S-BP-DP shows a decline as the sample size increases, dropping to 1%percent11\%1 % for n=500ğ‘›500n=500italic_n = 500. The regression parameter estimates from S-BP-N remain robust for all sample sizes, but the estimation of the link function deteriorates with an increase in sample size. Estimation of the link function and the regression parameters are seen to be poor under the S-BP-DP model. In summary, estimates from the GP models are seen to be robust under model misspecification. Estimation of the link function under the S-BP-N model tends to suffer for large sample sizes, while the S-BP-DP model delivers poor performances across all sample sizes.
